AGI - The confirmation that no one would want to receive came: The little Bibas are dead. Hamas announced today that the two brothers and their mother are among the four dead that will return Thursday. On Saturday the Palestinian group will release the last six hostages still alive.> The story of Shiri, 33 years old, and of the little Ariel and Kfir, at the time respectively of 4 years and nine months, had moved the world. Kfir was the smallest of hostages seized during the massacre of 7 October 2023. The photos of the children, both red-haired, have become one of the symbols of the tragedy. The three were taken away from Nir Oz's kibbutz along with the fourth family member, Yarden, 35, released on February 1, after 16 months of imprisonment. Immediately after his return, Yarden, who left the hospital in which he had been hospitalized in the last few weeks, begged the government to do everything to get his wife and children back. Despite the armed arm of Hamas - the Brigade Ezzedin al Qassam - had announced already in November 2023 the death of three of the four members from the Bibas family, of Argentine/Peruviane origins, Israel had never confirmed the news.
When the voice of the restitution of the corpses began to circulate, today, the government asked not to circulate indiscretions, but to provide the list was the head of the negotiators of Hamas, Khalil Al Hayy. And in spite of everything, Israel again chose the line of the reserve. To this uncertainty the Bibas family seems to cling again. "We are shocked," they said, but "until we receive the definitive confirmation, our journey is not finished." On Saturday will be the last six Israeli hostages still alive to return to Gaza. Among them also the Ethiopian Israeli Avera Mengistu and the Bedouin Hisham al-Sayed>, which nothing has to do with the tragedy of 2023: they had voluntarily entered Gaza, respectively in 2014 and 2015, where they were captured. For each Israeli hostage, 77 Palestinian prisoners will be released, <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-02-15/today-relax-Israeli-30030988/"> as provided for in the agreement </a>. Among them, 47 of the thousand prisoners who had been traded in 2011 with Israeli soldier Gilad Shalit, in the hands of Hamas for 5 years, and were then arrested again.
<
<div </div
</div
As reported by the media, Israel has finally committed itself to allowing the entry into Gaza of caravans and heavy equipment, gradually and controlled, as provided for in the agreement. But only once Hamas has respected his commitment to return the hostages he has suffered. The stage one of the agreement expires on March 1 and, despite the fears that with the return of all the hostages alive the war can begin again, Israel has ensured that this week the negotiations for phase two will begin. And you also look at the mid-long period. Israeli Foreign Minister, Gideon Saar, said that Israel demanded "a complete dismilitarization of the Gaza Strip" once the war ended: "We will not accept the continued presence of Hamas or any other terrorist group." And this is also the main clause that Saar has placed to evaluate the $20 billion Arab plan for the reconstruction of Gaza prepared by Egypt, alternative to the idea of American President Donald Trump to empty Gaza from its inhabitants and make it a tourist paradise.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In the proposal, that Egyptian President Abdel-Fattah al-Sisi will discuss Thursday at Riad, there is no place for Hamas. The formation of a Palestinian national committee is planned to govern Gaza > without the involvement of Hamas and international participation in reconstruction without moving Palestinians abroad. Reconstruction will take at least three years. According to the influential Republican Senator Lindsey Graham, the Arab Allies plan "will allow Palestinians to leave if they want it, but if they do not want it, they will be able to remain while reconstruction is underway." This, he stressed, could "show President Trump how to handle the Palestinian question without hunting everyone away". &nbsp;
