AGI - Mario Draghi 'super star' in the European Parliament. After his speech at the emicycle on the occasion of the event of the parliamentary week that gathers both MEPs and Members and Senators of the Member States, the former Prime Minister and former President of the BCE was surrounded by fans for selfies and photos. A young man convinced him to be autographed a five-euro note. "A birthday present for my partner," he explained. "Obviously, it's a banknote that reports his signature as a government of the BCE," he said. Another fan instead stopped him in the hallway to have an autograph on a flag of the European Union.&nbsp;
The former government gave a long speech to the EU parliament touching many points of interest to the Member States, with a clear message to unity to face and be protagonists of the challenges in the field.&nbsp;
"We can regain the ability to defend our interests. > And we can give hope to our people. The national governments and parliaments of our continent, the European Commission and Parliament are called to be the guardians of this hope at a turning point in the history of Europe.» If we join, we will be up to the challenge and succeed." This was stated by former President of the ECB and former Prime Minister, Mario Draghi, in his speech to the European Parliament for the parliamentary week 2025.
<h2> Security in Ukraine
"If recent statements outline our future, we can expect to be left largely alone to ensure security in Ukraine and Europe itself," said Draghi.
&nbsp;
<h2>" China, but also USA"</h2>
&nbsp;"When the report was written, the main geopolitical theme was the rise of China. Now, the EU will have to face tariffs by the new US administration in the coming months, hindering our access to our largest export market. In addition, the highest US tariffs on China will redirect Chinese overcapacity to Europe, further striking European companies. In fact, large EU companies are more concerned about this effect than for the loss of access to the US market." &nbsp;
&nbsp;"We could also address policies designed to attract European companies to produce more in the United States, based on lower taxes, cheaper energy and deregulation. The expansion of industrial capacity in the United States is a fundamental part of the government's plan to ensure that tariffs are not inflationary," added Draghi.
&nbsp;
<h2>"Nothing can be said
"Time ago, even before the conclusion of the report, I said to a meeting that cannot be said to the public debt, no to the Single Market, no to the creation of the Union of the capital market. We cannot say no to everything, otherwise we must be consistent, and admit that we cannot maintain the fundamental values for which this European Union has been created. So when you ask me what's best to do, I say I have no idea, but do something!" he said.&nbsp;
<h2> The challenge of AI</h2>
"Since the relationship (on competitiveness) has been published, the changes that took place are widely in line with the trends that had been outlined there. But the sense of urgency to undertake the radical change that the relationship supported has become even stronger" - added -&nbsp; "First of all, the pace of progress in artificial intelligence has accelerated rapidly. We have seen border models reach almost 90% accuracy in reference tests for scientific reasoning, exceeding the scores of human experts. We also saw models become much more efficient, with training costs falling by a factor ten and inference costs of a factor over twenty. For now, most progress is still taking place outside Europe. Eight of the current ten major language models have been developed in the United States, and the other two come from China. Every day we delay, the frontier of technology moves away> from us, but the falling costs are also an opportunity for us to recover faster"
&nbsp;
Energy prices
"Natural gas prices remain highly volatile, increasing by around 40% since September, and Gnl imports margins from the United States have increased significantly since last year. Energy prices are also generally increased in all countries and are still 2-3 times higher than in the United States. And we have seen the kind of internal tensions that might arise if we do not act urgently to face the challenges created by the energy transition."
"We must lower energy prices.> This has become imperative not only for traditional industries, but also for advanced technologies. It is estimated that the energy consumption of datacenters in Europe will more than triple by the end of the decade. But it is also increasingly clear that decarbonization >stessa can only be sustainable if its benefits are anticipated." &nbsp;
<br> "The report identifies a number of reasons for high energy prices in Europe, in addition to the fact that the EU is not an important natural gas producer: the limited coordination of natural gas supply, the operation of the energy market, the delays in the installation of renewable capacities, underdeveloped networks, high taxation and financial margins.> These and other factors are all of our creation and therefore can be changed if we have the will to do so," he adds.
"The report proposes several measures in this regard: reform of the energy market, greater transparency in energy trade, more extensive use of long-term energy contracts and long-term purchases of natural gas and massive investment in networks and interconnections. Moreover, it asks not only a faster installation of renewable energies, but also investments in clean basic generation and flexibility solutions that we can draw upon when renewable energies do not generate energy," says Draghi.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Stop auto endothermic motor
In the automotive sector, "it must align tools and objectives. You cannot impose the stop to combustion engines by saying to an entire production sector that must stop a large production line and at the same time do not impose, with the same force, the installation of charging systems > and do not create interconnections to do so. We must align things."
<h2> Common debt
&nbsp;"A question raised by many of you was financing. A premise: the amount of 750-800 billion euros of necessary investments. As I said before, this is a prudent estimate. Actually, it could be even higher if we consider that it does not include investment in climate change mitigation and other important goals. But this figure has been estimated on the basis of the current situation and, in this case, it is necessary to issue debt securities." &nbsp;
"And this common debt must be, by definition, supranational, because some countries have fiscal space, but not enough for their own objectives, while other countries have no fiscal space. However, keep in mind that this is only an estimate based on the current situation," he added.&nbsp;
<h2>Modernising the European industry
"In addition to acting to modernize the European economy, > we must manage the transition to our traditional industries. These industries remain important to Europe. Since 2012, the top 10 sectors with fastest growing productivity are almost entirely made up of so-called mid-tech sectors such as automotive and machinery. The manufacturing sector also employs around 30 million people, compared to 13 million in the United States. >And in this world where geopolitical relations evolve and protectionism increases, maintain sectors such as steel and chemicals that provide input to the entire economy and are essential for defence, has become strategic." This was stated by former President of the ECB and former Prime Minister, Mario Draghi, in his speech to the European Parliament for the parliamentary week 2025.
"To support traditional industries is often represented as a binary choice. We can choose to let them go and allow resources to move to new sectors; or we can sacrifice the development of new technologies and finally resign ourselves to a permanently low growth. But the choice doesn't have to be that clear. If we implement reforms to make Europe more innovative > we will alleviate many of the compromises between these objectives.<br> For example, if we exploit the economies of scale of our EU market and integrate our energy market, > we will lower production costs everywhere. So we will be in a better position to manage the potential relapses, for example, of low-cost energy supply to energy-intensive industries. If we offer a more competitive rate of return in Europe and more efficient capital markets, our savings will naturally remain at home. So we will have a wider private capital reserve to finance both new technologies and consolidated industries that maintain a competitive advantage," he added.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

